segments.text: I guess I'm looking and saying, you know, about policies and who makes them the big picture, who has the information.
Hopefully the commander in chief has it.
No, the question of policy is, you know, whose do you implement, which myth, mine, yours, how close to reality?
Do we continue even though we suddenly believe it may not be true?
It's easy to look back and say, yes, these were the key points, the dates.
We can mark them.
However, going in, it's sort of like the guy that goes out and he's told, go drain the swamp.
He goes out looking for the plug, and suddenly he finds himself waist deep in alligators.
By this time, you forget what your original mission was, drain the swamp.
You know, our problem is it's easy getting in.
We picked up for the French.
We reestablished France.
and tried to help them carry on the rebirth of the French colonial empire.
It was dead and gone.
We misread the signal.
Would Vietnam have been better off under a communist Ho Chi Minh to start with than it was later?
I'm not sure I say better off, but there would have been a million or two million less dead.
You know, history, the long history has to judge the question of better or worse.
Now, do we still believe our myths?
We still believe there are very few limits on power, even post-Vietnam.
You mean militarily?
Militarily.
We don't want to concede there are places we cannot go and things we cannot do.
We can start it, but can we get the American public to contribute enough johnnies?
You know, an operation that loses 30 lives is acceptable.
An operation that loses 300,000 may not be.
It's how many over how long a period of time.
Somewhere out here in America, there's this kind of barometer.
It says enough, enough is enough.
This thing leads nowhere.
Get out.
And I'm not sure we know where it is and what the number is.
If you did, you could sell it.
But I think at the start of Vietnam, the great consensus was it was a good and noble cause.
I think at the end, it was less of that.
And more of, why did we go?
Personally, I guess, you know, I look at it, you tell yourself, if you participated, you hope it was a good cause.
You better believe it was a good cause.
Because you'd really hate to think you spent your men, the equipment I could care less about, and the money.
You'd hate to think you spent your friends the other way.
That, uh,
Intelligent people don't spend many friends, but you see a lot of infantry guys go.
It's what were they spent for?
No.
What did we get back for what we expended?
And that's what I guess long-term that you would hope that whoever says we should go should ask the serious question, what do we expect to do?
And look at it in the cold light of day before you get in the swamp
can find yourself there.
Do you think that the military learned anything from... No.
You don't think the military's learned anything from the Vietnam experience?
I don't think the military as such learns very much from any war.
Because of the bureaucracy?
I think bureaucracy has its own inertia.
The men who learned
live.
They got out large extent.
It's a rapid turnover of personnel.
You did your two years.
You did whatever you were doing.
Listen, whatever you will be his office.
When the war ended, we cleaned the army out.
We cut back to the very bones.
The ones we kept with a bureaucratic oriented game players who look inward.
I'm not sure we as a country learned very much like wave the flag and have a cheap victory.
But make sure it's real quick and real cheap.
Behind all those planes, all those bombs, and one of the things I think a war that never changes, you have to have a guy with a rifle take the hill and hold it.
You must occupy the land and let's quit the game, let's attrit the enemy.
The game is not to attrit the enemy.
If there's a war, and I think war is a game, is let's make your side stop through the quickest means possible.
And say it with a face that says if that's walk from one end of your country to the other, do it.
If it's drop a nuke, do it.
If it's drop more than one nuke, use them.
It's like a street fight.
It's not who can fight the longest, who can kick the hardest.
It's who can kick the hardest the quickest.
We did a thing in Vietnam called slow escalation.
We staggered our troop buildups.
They staggered the rate of people coming down the Ho Chi Minh Trail.
They matched us man for man.
One thing I do want to say to clear up a thing on Vietnam about firepower and combat.
The supply in Vietnam was nine non-riflemen for each rifleman in the woods.
The height of Vietnam, 557,000 or so Americans.
We had approximately 57,000 riflemen scattered throughout the whole country.
If their units all fight as riflemen when need be, then revert back to something else.
We didn't.
We took all our creature comforts, our PX, our BX for the air base.
We took miniature American cities and made them in base camps, the enclaves.
We created America.
We took our TV station with us in Saigon.
You could see Bobby the Weather Girl who came home and killed herself later.

we had our own radio station because you didn't have to listen to that foreign sounding indigenous noise that was music we had our ghetto blasters the walkman radio which probably was as big as a truck in comparison to today we took america with us that's not how you win wars our commanders flew to the battlefield and flew home each day the generals died in the general's mess hall
with all the comforts any general of mess has, and I do not begrudge them their privilege of rank.
If you're fighting a war, gentlemen, let's fight a war.
Let's not serve tea as the British Army did.
It's not with the individual general of the province.
It's the system.
Play the game.
We did.
Our version of it, it didn't work.
Do you think that a while ago you said that the right amount of firepower applied at the right time and the right... that we could have won under certain conditions?
What do you think those conditions would have had to have been?
Pre-'68, you could have nuked Vietnam in 61, 62, 63, 64, 65.
Nobody could have done anything about it.
Two ports.
Haiphong Harbor was slow to be closed because at least 31 British merchant ships were in there unloading supplies.
That's your allies helping the enemy.
But remember, we had no constitutional enemy, no declaration of war.
If you're going to fight one, even without a declaration, make up your mind, I've got the bomb, I've got whatever weapons, let's use our technology.
One plane, better yet,
One missile, one city gone, phone them and ask them, do you need demonstration number two?
But remember, when you play with those at that level, if the other side opts in, you've got a problem.
It's how far do you go.
Go win and go stay home.
Total commitment.
Yeah, which we didn't have.
We didn't have total commitment.
We piecemealed it.
It's war on the cheap.
The way it reflects our economy, our government, our attitude.
How little can we get by with?
Piecemeal.
So we piecemealed out at least eight years of American youth and decided to end the meal that wasn't satisfying.
And then let's pretend for the next 10 years it didn't happen.
And probably the greatest legacy, I guess if there's a legacy of Vietnam,
There's always going to be a simple question hard to answer, why?
And I don't have one for that.
If you want to say I have myths, they did.
But when you get into the why, I still think there's a...
If it was a good cause, then it was worth going for.
If it wasn't, we should have stayed home.
And
I don't think there's an easy way to reconcile, even for the guys that lived through it and came back, there's an easy way to reconcile what you say about your friends to people you met that didn't.
That's the unfinished business in America.
I think the first time I saw what they were going to build as a monument in Washington, how stupid.
I think the longer I've looked at it in a way, how fascinating.
You know, I might offer for all presidents of the United States, after being sworn in as commander-in-chief, their first stop is take a walk to the wall.
Don't pause.
Read all the names, Mr. President.
You'll be there a long time.
But let's make sure we understand what we're expending.
You're not expending one grave marker.
Put them all out there.
Maybe the best thing for that, to ask yourself the question, you know, who?
Well, we know who.
Why?
That's not on the wall.
Never will be.
We can play with the statues in front of it, the three riflemen.
Fascinating enough, if you'll look at the statue, it's one black, one Anglo, one Hispanic.
Grunts.
The towel around the neck, the Vietnam clothing, the machine gun, the rifle.
Now the nurses want their statues.
Could be sarcastic and say with bedpan.
Eight nurses died in Vietnam, at least, maybe more, at least the ones I've read about.
I'm not sure how many, you know, who do we put a statue up next for, gays, who went, whatever.
You know, I'm not sure how much you can change and have it still be that.
But then again, who should decide what it is?
I'm not sure it ought to be a commission or not be a commission.
They got in Washington and leave that.
I think the wall should serve as a reminder to those who commit Americans.
It's not out of sight.
That's one right there in Washington.
Maybe we should build one for each war.
You know, I'm not sure what you do about the others.
A lot of them want the statue for those.
And the compromise was for those who live to come home, the three rivalries.
Do you build them next to the doctors and the nurses?
I don't know.
We leave it at that.
It's much like the war in Vietnam, but not an easy answer.
In fact, there's no answer.
Is there anything you'd like to add?
You know, I guess one remark somebody wanted to say, you know, sum it up.
You've got two minutes.
to any president or anybody who has an idea to save somebody.
A cheap, quick answer is please do not let Vietnam stand in the way.
Look at the question asked if the cause is right and just, don't hesitate.
If there's a question of morality of what you're doing, never do it.
But having made the decision to do it if it's just and right,
Then get on with doing it.
But one line thing is, go to win or go stay home.
Thank you.
Glad to help.
